'''''Capsicum chinense''''' is a species of [[chile peppers]] that includes the following [[variety (biology)|varieties]]:

* [[Adjuma]] ([[Suriname]])
* Aj<U+00ED> Limo or Naucho ([[Peru]])
* [[Aj<U+00ED> dulce]] ([[Venezuela]])
* [[Datil pepper|Datil]] ([[Florida]])
* [[Fatalii]] (South central Africa)
* [[Habanero chile]] ([[Cuba]] and [[Yucat<U+00E1>n Peninsula|Yucat<U+00E1>n]])
** Habanero cultivar [[Red Savina pepper]]
* [[Madame Jeanette]] ([[Haiti]])
* [[Naga Morich]] ([[Bangladesh]])
** Naga Morich cultivar [[Dorset Naga pepper]]
* [[Naga Jolokia pepper]] ([[Bangladesh]])
* [[Scotch bonnet]] ([[Jamaica]])

''Capsicum chinense'' or "Chinese capsicum" is a misnomer since all ''capsica'' originate in the [[New World]]. [[Nikolaus Joseph von Jacquin]] (1727-1817), an [[Austria|Austrian]] [[Botany|botanist]], erroneously named the species in 1776, because he believed that they originated in [[China]].<ref>[http://www.hort.purdue.edu/newcrop/proceedings1996/V3-479.html Bosland, P.W. 1996. Capsicums: Innovative uses of an ancient crop. ''p. 479-487. In: J. Janick (ed.), Progress in new crops. ASHS Press, Arlington, VA.'']</ref>

